The '''War on Terror''' (also known as the '''Global War on Terror''' and '''War on Terrorism''') is a term commonly applied to an international military campaign begun in 2001 by the [[United States]] and the [[United Kingdom]], with support from other countries. The campaign's initial purpose was to eliminate [[al-Qaeda]] and other militant organizations.<ref name="WH 10-07-01">[[ETA]]
{{cite press release
|publisher=The White House
(Clockwise, starting at top left:Burning ruins of the [[World Trade Center]], US soldiers board a Chinook helicopter during [[Operation Anaconda]], an Afghan and US soldier stand by to engage an enemy, a car bomb detonates in Baghdad, Iraq
|date=11 September 2001
|title=Presidential Address to the Nation
|url=http://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2001/10/print/20011007-8.html}}</ref>

The phrase 'War on Terror' was first used by [[President of the United States|US President]] [[George W. Bush]] on 20 September 2001. The Bush administration and the Western media have since used the term to denote a global military, political, legal and ideological struggle—targeting both organizations designated as terrorist and regimes accused of supporting them. It was typically used with a particular focus on [[Islamic terrorism|militant Islamists]] and al-Qaeda.

Although the term is not officially used by the administration of US President [[Barack Obama]] (which instead uses the term '''Overseas Contingency Operation'''), it is still commonly used by politicians, in the media and officially by some aspects of government, such as the [[United States Armed Forces|United States']] [[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]

==Terminology==
The phrase "War on Terror" has been used to specifically refer to the ongoing military campaign led by the US, UK and their allies against organizations and regimes identified by them as terrorist, and excludes other independent [[counter-terrorism|counter-terrorist operations and campaigns]] such as those by [[Russia]] and [[India]]. The conflict has also been referred to by names other than the War on Terror.  It has also been known as:
*[[World War III]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200605/s1632213.htm|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110204112337/http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200605/s1632213.htm|archivedate=4 February 2011 |title=Bush likens 'war on terror' to WWIII|publisher=  ABC News Online – Abc.net.au |date=06/05/2006 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/13/opinion/foreign-affairs-world-war-iii.html?sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all |title=Foreign Affairs; World War III |author=Thomas L. Friedman |date=13 September 2009 |work=New York Times |accessdate=10 November 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2004-03-12/news/18257093_1_al-qaeda-mayor-bloomberg-basque |title=World War II Strikes Spain |date=12 March 2004 |work=Daily News |location=New York |accessdate=10 November 2009  |deadurl=yes}}</ref>
*World War IV<ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-CIA director: U.S. faces 'World War IV' |author=Charles Feldman and Stan Wilson |newspaper=CNN |date=3 April 2003 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/US/04/03/sprj.irq.woolsey.world.war/ |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080727025549/http://www.cnn.com/2003/US/04/03/sprj.irq.woolsey.world.war/index.html|archivedate=27 July 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/1427428/We-want-them-to-be-nervous-That-means-you-Ali-Bashar-and-Kim.html |title='We want them to be nervous' (That means you Ali, Bashar and Kim) |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=9 November 2009  | first=Julian | last=Coman | date=13 April 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opinionjournal.com/editorial/feature.html?id=95001493 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20040406043752/http://www.opinionjournal.com/editorial/feature.html?id=95001493 |archivedate=6 April 2004 |title=World War IV |author=Elio A. Cohen |date=20 November 2001 |work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=9 November 2009 }}</ref> (assuming the [[Cold War]] was World War III)
*Bush's War on Terror<ref>{{cite news|last=Thompson |first=Mark |url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1868367,00.html |title=The $1 Trillion Bill for Bush's War on Terror |work=TIME |date=26 December 2008 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/22/AR2009012203929.html |title=Bush's 'War' On Terror Comes to a Sudden End |work=The Washington Post |date= 23 January 2009|accessdate=26 March 2011 |first=Dana |last=Priest}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/01/28/terror/main3757858.shtml |title=Bush's War On Terror Shifting Targets |publisher=CBS News |date=28 January 2008 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>
*The Long War<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.org/Press/Commentary/ed090803a.cfm |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20050909202409/http://www.heritage.org/Press/Commentary/ed090803a.cfm |archivedate=9 September 2005 |title=The Long War Against Terrorism |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=9 September 2005 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref><ref name="WaPo">"Abizaid Credited With Popularizing the Term 'Long War'", 3 February 2006: Washington Post traces history of the phrase "Long War" [http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/02/02/AR2006020202242.html]</ref>
*The Global War of Terror<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jfcom.mil/about/com_jfic.htm |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20050204124824/http://www.jfcom.mil/about/com_jfic.htm |archivedate=4 February 2005 |title=Joint Forces Intelligence Command. |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=4 February 2005 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://8tharmy.korea.army.mil/35ada/dco.html |title=Eric L. Bradley, Deputy Commander |publisher=8tharmy.korea.army.mil |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bisp.gov.pk/Default3.aspx |title=Compensation Package for Bomb Blast Victims. |publisher=Bisp.gov.pk |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref>
*The War Against al-Qaeda<ref>{{cite web|last=Lucas |first=Fred |url=http://www.cnsnews.com/node/59446 |title=Obama Declares America ‘At War’ with Al Qaeda, Offers New Security Initiatives |publisher=CNSnews.com |date=7 January 2010 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2007-02-20/opinion/17233057_1_al-qaeda-terror-promotion-of-human-rights | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Glenn | last=Sulmasy | title=A new look for the war on al Qaeda | date=20 February 2007}}</ref>

In 1984 the [[Reagan Administration]] used the term "war against terrorism" as part of an effort to pass legislation that was designed to freeze assets of terrorist groups and marshal the forces of government against them. Author Shane Harris asserts this was a reaction to the [[1983 Beirut barracks bombing]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Silver |first=Alexandra |url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1973131,00.html |title=How America Became a Surveillance State |work=Time Magazine |date=18 March 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>

The concept of America at war with terrorism may have begun on September 11, 2001 when [[Tom Brokaw]], having just witnessed the collapse of one the towers of the [[World Trade Center]], declared "Terrorists have declared war on [America]."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.nbclearn.com/portal/site/k-12/flatview?cuecard=1419 |title=Breaking News on September 11th |author=[[Matt Lauer]] |author2=[[Katie Couric]] |author3=Tom Brokaw |date=11 September 2001 |work=NBC Learn K-12 |publisher=NBCUniversal Media |accessdate=11 September 2012}}</ref> 

On 16 September 2001, at [[Camp David]], President George W. Bush used the phrase ''war on terrorism'' in an unscripted and controversial comment when he said, "This crusade – this war on terrorism – is going to take a while, ... "<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2001/09/17/2001-09-17_a_fight_vs__evil__bush_and_c.html|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100505200651/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2001/09/17/2001-09-17_a_fight_vs__evil__bush_and_c.html|archivedate=5 May 2010 |title=Kenneth R. Bazinet, "A Fight Vs. Evil, Bush And Cabinet Tell U.S." |work=Daily News |location=New York |date=17 September 2001 |accessdate=26 March 2011 }}</ref>  Bush later apologized for this remark due to the negative connotations the term ''crusade'' has to people of Muslim faith.  The word ''crusade'' was not used again.<ref>Jonathan Lyons, "Bush enters Mideast's rhetorical minefield" (Reuters: 21 September 2001). [http://hv.greenspun.com/bboard/q-and-a-fetch-msg.tcl?msg_id=006SM3 Greenspun.com]</ref>  On 20 September 2001, during a televised address to a joint session of congress, Bush stated that, "(o)ur 'war on terror' begins with al-Qaeda, but it does not end there.  It will not end until every terrorist group of global reach has been found, stopped and defeated."<ref name=cnntranscript>{{cite news|title=Transcript of President Bush's address |publisher=CNN |date= 20 September 2001 |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2001/US/09/20/gen.bush.transcript/}}</ref>  Bush did not say when he expected this would be achieved.

US President Barack Obama has rarely used the term, but in his inaugural address on 20 January 2009, he stated "Our nation is at war, against a far-reaching network of violence and hatred."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Inauguration/story?id=6689022&page=1 |title=FULL TRANSCRIPT: President Barack Obama's Inaugural Address|publisher=ABC News |date=20 January 2009 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref> In March 2009 the Defense Department officially changed the name of operations from "Global War on Terror" to "Overseas Contingency Operation" (OCO).<ref name=oco-wapost>[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/24/AR2009032402818.html 'Global War On Terror' Is Given New Name], Scott Wilson and Al Kamen, ''[[The Washington Post]]'', 25 March 2009; Page A04</ref> In March 2009, the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] requested that [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] staff members avoid use of the term, instead using "Overseas Contingency Operation".<ref name=oco-wapost/>

In April 2007 the British government announced publicly that it was abandoning the use of the phrase "War on Terror" as they found it to be less than helpful.<ref>{{cite web|last= Reynolds|first=Paul |date=17 April 2007 |title=Declining use of 'war on terror' |publisher=BBC |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6562709.stm}}.</ref> This was explained more recently by Lady [[Eliza Manningham-Buller]]. In her 2011 [[Reith lecture]], the former head of [[MI5]] said that the 9/11 attacks were "a crime, not an act of war.", "So I never felt it helpful to refer to a war on terror".<ref>{{cite news |last=Norton-Taylor |first=Richard |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2 September 2011 |title=MI5 former chief decries 'war on terror' |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2011/sep/02/mi5-war-on-terror-criticism}}</ref>

Both the term and the policies it denotes have been a source of ongoing controversy, as critics argue it has been used to justify unilateral [[preventive war]], human rights abuses and other violations of [[international law]].<ref>Borhan Uddin Khan and Muhammad Mahbubur Rahman, “Combating Terrorism under Human Rights and Humanitarian Law Regime”, Mediterranean Journal of Human Rights, Vol. 12 (Double Issue), 2008, pp.379–397.</ref><ref>
{{cite web
|url= http://www.amnestyusa.org/our-work/issues/security-and-human-rights?id=1108209|title= Civil Rights and the "War on Terror"
|work=amnestyusa.org
|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref>

==Precursor to the 9/11 attacks==
{{See also|Terrorism|List of terrorist incidents}}
The origins of al-Qaeda as a network inspiring terrorism around the world and training operatives can be traced to the [[Soviet war in Afghanistan]] (December 1979 – February 1989). The United States supported the [[Islamism|Islamist]] [[mujahadeen]] [[guerilla warfare|guerillas]] against the military forces of the [[Soviet Union]] and the [[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cooley|first=John K.|authorlink=John K. Cooley|title=Unholy Wars: Afghanistan, America and International Terrorism|work=[[Demokratizatsiya (journal)|Demokratizatsiya]]|date=Spring 2003|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3996/is_200304/ai_n9199132|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080219234628/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3996/is_200304/ai_n9199132|archivedate=19 February 2008|format=reprint}}</ref> In May 1996 the group World Islamic Front for Jihad Against Jews and Crusaders (WIFJAJC), sponsored by [[Osama bin Laden]] and later reformed as al-Qaeda, started forming a large base of operations in [[Afghanistan]], where the [[Islamism|Islamist]] extremist regime of the Taliban had seized power that same year.<ref>The group was also responsible for the [[1993 World Trade Center bombing]].
{{cite news
|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/dec/06/news/mn-12224
|title=Fighters Hunt Former Ally
|date=6 December 2001
|author=Megan K. Stack
|work=Los Angeles Times 
|accessdate=2 May 2010}}
</ref> In February 1998, Osama bin Laden signed a [[fatwā]], as the head of al-Qaeda, [[Declaration of war|declaring war]] on the West and [[Israel]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Al Qaeda's Fatwa |url=http://www.pbs.org/newshour/terrorism/international/fatwa_1998.html |newspaper=[[PBS Newshour]] |date=23 February 1998 |accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fbi.gov/news/testimony/al-qaeda-international |title=Al-Qaeda International |author=J. T. Caruso |date=8 December 2001 |work=Federal Bureau of Investigation |publisher=United States Department of Justice |accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref> later in May of that same year al-Qaeda released a video declaring war on the US and the West.<ref>{{cite news |title=Previously unseen tape shows bin Laden's declaration of war |author=Nic Robertson |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2002-08-19/us/terror.tape.main_1_bin-international-islamic-front-osama?_s=PM:US |newspaper=CNN |date=19 August 2002 |accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Osama bin Laden: missed opportunities |author=Lisa Myers |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/4540958/ns/nightly_news/t/osama-bin-laden-missed-opportunities/ |newspaper=NBC |date=17 March 2004 |accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref>

